@[Meta](author="Samin Yeasar" date="2026-07-03" title="Phase 8: Professional Math")

= Professional Math in Vell

This document demonstrates Vell's Phase 8 math engine: numbered equations, theorem environments, and
math environment directives.

== Numbered Equations

A simple numbered equation with a label:

@[Equation](label="e:mass-energy" source="E = mc^2")

An unlabeled equation still gets a number:

@[Equation](source="\\int_{-\\infty}^{\\infty} e^{-x^2} \\, dx = \\sqrt{\\pi}")

Multiple equations auto-increment:

@[Equation](label="e:pythagoras" source="a^2 + b^2 = c^2")

== Theorem Environments

@[Theorem](label="thm:pythagoras" name="Pythagoras") {
  For any right triangle with legs *a*, *b* and hypotenuse *c*:

  $$
  a^2 + b^2 = c^2
  $$
}

@[Proof]() {
  Consider a square of side *a* + *b*. Its area is (a + b)(a + b). Arrange four copies of the triangle
  inside. The remaining area equals c sup 2. But (a + b)(a + b) expands to a-squared + 2ab +
  b-squared, and the four triangles have area 2ab. Therefore c-squared equals a-squared + b-squared.
}

@[Lemma](name="Triangle Inequality") {
  For any triangle with sides *a*, *b*, *c*:

  $$
  a + b \\geq c
  $$

  with equality only in the degenerate case.
}

@[Corollary](name="Reverse Triangle Inequality") {
  For any triangle with sides *a*, *b*, *c*:

  $$
  |a - b| \\leq c
  $$
}

@[Definition](name="Prime Number") {
  A natural number *p* > 1 is *prime* if its only positive divisors are 1 and *p* itself.
}

@[Example]() {
  The prime numbers less than 20 are:

  $$
  2, 3, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17, 19
  $$
}

@[Remark]() {
  The number 1 is neither prime nor composite by convention.
}

@[Axiom](name="Euclid's Fifth Postulate") {
  If a line segment intersects two straight lines forming two interior angles on the same side that
  sum to less than two right angles, then the two lines, if extended indefinitely, meet on that side.
}

@[Conjecture](name="Goldbach's Conjecture") {
  Every even integer greater than 2 can be expressed as the sum of two primes.
}

@[Proposition](name="Sum of First n Naturals") {
  For any positive integer *n*:

  $$
  \\sum_{k=1}^{n} k = \\frac{n(n+1)}{2}
  $$
}

== Align Environment

@[Align](source="(a + b)^2 &= a^2 + 2ab + b^2 \\\\ (a - b)^2 &= a^2 - 2ab + b^2") {
  The align environment supports multi-line equations.
}

== Matrix Environment

@[PMatrix](source="\\begin{pmatrix} a & b \\\\ c & d \\end{pmatrix}") {
  A matrix with parentheses delimiters.
}

== Cases Environment

@[Cases](source="f(x) = \\begin{cases} x^2 & \\text{if } x \\geq 0 \\\\ -x^2 & \\text{if } x < 0 \\end{cases}") {
  A piecewise function definition.
}

== Combined Usage

@[Theorem](label="thm:ftc" name="Fundamental Theorem of Calculus") {
  Let *f* be a continuous real-valued function on an interval. Then:

  @[Equation](source="\\frac{d}{dx} \\int_a^x f(t) \\, dt = f(x)")

  @[Equation](source="\\int_a^b f(x) \\, dx = F(b) - F(a)")
}

@[Proof]() {
  By the definition of the derivative and the first fundamental theorem:

  @[Equation](source="F'(x) = \\lim_{h \\to 0} \\frac{1}{h} \\int_x^{x+h} f(t) \\, dt = f(x)")
}

== Cross-References

Reference equation @[Ref](label="e:mass-energy") (the mass-energy equivalence) and equation
@[Ref](label="e:pythagoras") (the Pythagorean theorem).

Theorem @[Ref](label="thm:pythagoras") proves the same relationship, while @[Ref](label="thm:ftc")
connects differentiation and integration.

> [!NOTE]
> Cross-references resolve labels like `e:mass-energy` and `thm:pythagoras` to their numbered targets
> automatically.
